When the Madd is in the middle of the word (beginning or end doesn't count), 
you must extend for 5 Harakat (or 2.5 second) ^YCdG80ZB

When the Madd is at the end of the word
then you can optionally extend for 5harakat
(if you opt for not extending for 5 harakat
then you still have to extend for 2 harakat) ^Xb4t85tn

The letters of natural madd are: ^IhSHOPWo

Madd are proceeded by short vowels (Fatha, Damma, Kasra)
Madd extend the word for 2 harakat (1 second) ^o9PMk3ka

Natural Madd letters have smaller version:  ^aaHyL11r

Linking Madd happens when the Madd is situated between
two word, not in the first word nor in the second  ^ZHzP0mf9

When there is Linking Madd, if you are continuously reciting from word 1
to word 2, then you have to extend for 2 Harakat. But if you decide to stop
at word 1 and continue from word 2, then the Madd shall not be pronounced  ^w7C2Na2o

Word 1 ^BEhUCVym

Word 2 ^T9Lw6QOX

Linking Madd is only made up of two letters: ^Hd7W3U48

Madd lazem occurs when Madd is followed by Sukkon.
When this happens we have to extend for 6 Harakat (3 seconds) ^EWBpa7zQ

Sukoon letters ^tukCPEls

is made up of three 'forms' ^ru1c5gnX

Shaddah sign ^lBCLJPRP

Sukoon sign
 ^wr5gEmyF

are the separate letters found
in some beginnings of surahs ^mzckFBnU

is the '  ' sign ^TsIdvW6a

there is the sukoon
sign after the Madd
so we extend for 
3 seconds ^pY94O7Hk

is the '  ' sign ^vYAp7lG0

Shaddah is just the sukoon sigh
combined the short vowel ^iKCwj2eg

there is the shaddah sign
so we extend for 
3 seconds ^4CcgOPA9

Temporary Madd is when the Madd letter is the second last letter of the word.
In this case, you have the option to extend for 1 second, 2 second or 3 seconds ^fLEFHXXx

This type of Madd is found at the end of verses. If you continue reading from
verse 1 to 2, then you should only extend for 1 second ^kN5oALoE

Once you decide which number of seconds you will extend for, you have to stick with it and use that
for the rest of your recitation  ^IWZcaUwl
